<ce:para>The wide-spread use of hydrogen powered fuel cell vehicles is limited by the lack of a viable storage technology for hydrogen. The DOE targets for system gravimetric densities are 6-9 wt%. Current reversible hydrogen storage materials do not meet this goal. A novel approach has been proposed recently which obtains hydrogen from the complex metal hydrides such as alanates, amides and borohydrides. The hydrides of period 2 and 3 metals have relatively high hydrogen densities but are thermodynamically very stable and do not release hydrogen until temperatures of 250Â°C or higher are reached. Vajo et al. have shown that the thermodynamics of the reaction can be modified by using additives to form compounds in the dehydrogenated state that are stable with respect to the constituents of the initial reaction.(1) The principle underlying this concept is that having a stabilized dehydrogenated state reduces the enthalpy of dehydrogenation and increases the equilibrium partial pressure of the dehydrogenation reaction. Our first principles density functional calculations have shown that it is possible to accurately predict the thermodynamics of these destabilized reactions, opening the way to use computational methods to guide experiments in the search for new destabilization compounds. We have computed the enthalpy of reaction for many combinations of reactants and products. We discuss calculation of dissociation pressures and kinetic information for the most promising of these materials.</ce:para>
